@cindex normalization
@tex
Given no @var{mask} or @var{weight}, the average of $x$ is defined as:  
$$
\bar x_j = {\sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} x_i \over N } 
$$
$N$ is the number of input elements contributing to each element in the
output. 
In this example $N$ is simply the product of the sizes of all dimensions
which are averaged over (i.e., dimensions specified with @samp{-a}).
The total sum in the numerator is, by default, normalized by the
@dfn{tally}.
In this case the tally is $N$, since there is no masking condition. 
In general the tally counts only the number of $x$'s which contribute to
the output average.
This may differ from $N$ when there is a condition, such as a
@dfn{masking condition}, on the average.  
Note that $\bar x_j$ represents just the $j$'th element of the output  
hyperslab.
The size $J$ of the output hyperslab for a given variable is the product
of all the dimensions of the input variable which are not averaged over.

Given a @var{weight} $w$ (specified with @samp{-w}), but no @var{mask},
the average of $x$ generalizes to:  
$$
\bar x_j = {\sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} w_i x_i \over N \sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} w_i} 
$$
As in the previous example, the tally is the product of the sizes of the
averaging dimensions (i.e., the dimensions specified with @samp{-a}).  
Notice the total sum in the numerator is, by default, normalized by both
the tally, $N$, and the sum of the @var{weights}, $\sum w_i$.

Given a @var{mask} (specified with @samp{-m}), but no @var{weight}
$w$, the average of $x$ is defined as: 
$$
\bar x_j = {\sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} m_i x_i \over \sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} m_i} 
$$
Here the tally, $\sum m_i$, is not necessarily equal to $N$.
The $m_i$ are the Boolean results of the @dfn{masking condition} for
points $x_i$. 
Thus $m_i = 1$ when the masking condition is @dfn{true} and $m_i = 0$
otherwise.   
The definition of the masking condition is given below.

The total sum in the numerator is, by default, normalized by the tally,
$\sum m_i$. 
When a @var{mask} is specified (with @samp{-m}), the tally is less than
the product of the sizes of the averaging dimensions whenever the
masking condition is false for at least one of the $N$ elements of the
input hyperslab.   
For each point where masking condition is @dfn{true}, the tally is
incremented by one.
But elements which do not meet the masking condition do not contribute
to the output average, and hence do not contribute to the tally.

Given a @var{mask} $m$ (specified with @samp{-m}), and @var{weight} $w$
(specified with @samp{-w}), the average of $x$ is defined as:  
$$
\bar x_j = {\sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} m_i w_i x_i \over \sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} m_i
\sum_{i = 1}^{i = N} m_i w_i} 
$$
This is the most general case handled by @code{ncwa}.
This case reduces to the simplest case when $w$ is 1 and the masking
condition is always true so $m_i = 1$. 
The total sum in the numerator is, by default, normalized by both the
tally, $\sum m_i$, and the sum of the weights contributing to the output
average, $\sum m_i w_i$. 
@end tex

